com.manyangled.snowball.analysis.interpolation

Class MonotonicSplineInterpolator

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.manyangled.snowball.analysis.interpolation.MonotonicSplineInterpolator
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    org.apache.commons.math3.analysis.interpolation.UnivariateInterpolator

    public class MonotonicSplineInterpolator
extends java.lang.Object
implements org.apache.commons.math3.analysis.interpolation.UnivariateInterpolator
    Interpolates data using a spline that is constrained to be monotonic non-decreasing.

    • Method Detail

      • interpolate

        public org.apache.commons.math3.analysis.polynomials.PolynomialSplineFunction interpolate(double[] x,
                                                                                          double[] y)
        Given data (x1, y1), (x2, y2)..., fit an interpolating spline that is constrained to be monotonic.
        Specified by:
        interpolate in interface org.apache.commons.math3.analysis.interpolation.UnivariateInterpolator
        Parameters:
        x - the x data x1, x2, ...
        y - the y data y1, y2, ...
        Returns:
        a polynomial spline that interpolates the data, and is monotonic non-decreasing over its interpolation domain.

        NOTE: the number of data provided must be ≥ (m + 3), where (m) is the number of spline intervals configured. See the setM method below.

      • setM

        public void setM(int m)
        Set the number of piecewise polynomial intervals over the interpolation domain.
        Parameters:
        m - the number of piecewise intervals.

        NOTE: m is currently required to be ≥ 4, due to internal numeric considerations. (m + 3) is also expected to be ≤ the number of data points provided for interpolation. for example, if m is set to 5, then at least 8 data points must be provided for interpolation.

      • setLambda

        public void setLambda(double lambda)
        Set the smoothing parameter for the spline fitting
        Parameters:
        lambda - the smoothing parameter. lambda is > 0. Larger values increase bias toward smoothing. Defaults to 1.

      • setBounds

        public void setBounds(double xMin,
                      double xMax)
        Set the interpolation domain for the fitting. Values outside this domain will be considered illegal.
        Parameters:
        xMin - the lower bound of the domain. Defaults to minimum x data value.
        xMax - the upper bound of the domain. Defaults to maximum x data value.

      • setW

        public void setW(double... w)
        Set the weights for data points. Higher weights at (x, y) increase bias toward fitting an interpolation that passes close to (x, y).
        Parameters:
        w - the weight vector. Must be same length as data. Defaults to [1, 1, 1... ].

      • addEqualityConstraint

        public void addEqualityConstraint(double x,
                                  double y)
        Add a hard equality constraint that the interpolation s(x) = y.
        Parameters:
        x - the x value of the constraint
        y - the value that the interpolation s(x) is constrained to equal.

      • addGradientEqualityConstraint

        public void addGradientEqualityConstraint(double x,
                                          double dydx)
        Add a hard equality constraint that the derivative of interpolation s'(x) = dydx.
        Parameters:
        x - the x value of the constraint
        dydx - the value that the interpolation derivative s'(x) is constrained to equal.

        NOTE: dydx must be ≥ 0, to be consistent with monotonic interpolation.

      • addLessThanConstraint

        public void addInterpolationOptions(org.apache.commons.math3.optim.OptimizationData... opts)
        Pass additional options to the internal interpolation routines.
        Parameters:
